{"key":"post-9430858","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9430858</id>\n<content>The truth is, you probably don't 'need' to fan at all with a shotgun, but as soon as I say that, someone will get a case of cobweb mold from still air.&amp;nbsp;  If there's good circulation in your house and you're growing a CO2 tolerant species such as cubensis, you really don't &lt;i&gt;have&lt;/i&gt; to fan.&amp;nbsp; However, air exchange is the number 1 pinning trigger, so it never hurts to have as much as possible.&amp;nbsp; Mist as required to make up for any lost moisture from fresh air exchange.&amp;nbsp; Nobody can say how often to mist, because too many variables are at play.&amp;nbsp; You have to use your eyeballs and a good hygrometer to know how often.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Mist the cakes and perlite.&amp;nbsp; The old advice to mist the walls only makes about as much sense as washing your car by spraying the hose on the ground around it.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9431145</next>\n<prev>9430352</prev>\n<first>9429286</first>\n<last>9439075</last>\n<when>1229292917</when>\n<utime>12/15/08 12:15 AM</utime>\n</post>"}